My name is Mikayla Maukula. I am an acrobat for the Ringling Brother's Circus. I am going to tell you about a typical day as being a performer in the circus.         6:30 A.M.- I wake up, get dreesed in normal day clothes, and go to the pie car for whole grain toast, bacon, and eggs. The show crews are setting up tents, lights, music,and the stage for tonight's show.         8:00 A.M.- School time. Since there are is no actual school around all of the kids go into a one-room schoolhouse that travels with the circus. Like normal schools we have computers, tests, and the worst, report cards. Most of my classmates don't speak English because the performers come from all over the world. As do our geography lessons.         2:00 P.M.- Finally, school is over. Time for a quick break. The clowns let me play with their unicycles and other silly equipment. I also get to play with my Afghan Hound, Sparky. I'd like to join a tennis team, but we're never in one place in order to stay on a team.        3:00 P.M.- Chores and practice. I have to feed and groom all of the animals, except for the ones that the trainers are taming. Today my dad's girlfriend and I are practicing out tricks on the silk ropes. When we are done we have to do some extreme stretching.          6:30 P.M.- Dinnertime. My family and I go to the pie car to eat, but we don't eat much because we're performing in two hours. We do ten shows a week: one each weekday, plus a manitee on Friday, and three on the weekends.          8:30 P.M.- Show time. During the show the clowns's are first, second, and third. After, the clowns's first act come the acrobats, that's me. Next, the clowns again.Then, the tricksters, the random and dangerous tricks people go. Finally, everyone comes out and goes bananas.          9:00 P.M.- Bed time. I'm thinking about the end of our touring season. It will be nice to go back to our real home in Maryland. When I grow up, will I still be in the performing industry like my parents? Who knows? The circus is fun an all, but it is a tough life.

Life In the Circus       Every day I wake up to the sound of horses trotting along the path with their hooves againsed the ground,'click clack click clack.' All of the clowns, acrobats, and trapeze artists are getting ready for the big show. I step out of bed and run through all of the big tents set up for the circus. I keep running until I bump into Dad. 'Hello sweatheart what are you up to,' he said in a nice voice. 'I want to help you groom the horses for the big show. Everything must be perfect,' I replied. 'I just did that. Why don't you go get some breakfast,' he said back. So I start to run and run again.                 I keep running until I make it to the pancake booth. 'Can I have a chocolate chip pancake with surup?'Of course you can Sophie. anything for the circus owner's daughter,' the pancake guy said. It's funny how every body knows my name when I don't know their's. I then ran back to my bed and took a long long nap.                    I woke up again at three a clock. Our firs show started in five minutes! I ran to the big tent and found a spot in the crowd. The circus was great with dancing elephants, flipping acrobats, and swinging trapeze artists. It was so amazing. After it ended I went to congradulate the preformers. they work so hard. I was so pleased and couldn't wait until the next show!

My Life in the Circus                    I, Tess U-vongcharoen is a circus tightrope walker. I have been a circus performer since I was ten years old. I had always wanted to be in a circus. Once my parents found out my talent for balancing on a tightrope, they knew that instant to sign me up to be a circus performer. My dream came true that very day.             When I started performing in the circus I was very shy and always nervous before a show. I didn't make any friends when I first started. When ever I practiced I would always be nervous and fall down. I don't know how many times I fell down, but I knew I fell down a lot. Next week I didn't make any friends, but I was falling off the tightrope less. I was feeling more confident.

Things That Happen in a Circus                            There are many things that happen in a circus. One of them is tightrope walking. Tightrope walking takes a lot of balance and determination. You need to walk carefully and try not to fall a lot. But if you practice a lot and maintain a lot of balance, you wouldn't have to fall a lot. You'll still need determination.  Determination leads you to a better life or a better try to stay on balance.                         Another thing that happens is clowning around. Clowns try to annoy or scare spectators with getting in front of their faces or squirting whem with squirt guns or those prank flowers that shoot out water. You wouldn't have to have determination. You need annoyance. So it'll be a lot easier to clown around.                 The last thing that happens is shooting out of a cannon.You won't need annything but firepower. Firepower helps circus actors fly( or rocket) out of the cannon and probably blast through the tent. Rocketing out of cannons would let actors know how it feels to fly aimlessly in the air. It'll help them to not be scared of heights.

You might think that circus is all fun and nonstop play, but it is really a whole lot of work. You have to spend a long time away from your home and practice really hard. But circus has some upsides too, like traveling around the world and meeting new people. One of the most exciting things is you learn new things along the way!       First, I wake up really early and get dressed. After I am dressed I go to the pie car for breakfast. And when I have gobbled down all of my food I go up to the trailor and practice my performance while the crewmen outside are setting up tents, lights, and music for tonight's show.       Next, it is school time. We have a one room schoolhouse travels with us. Our schoolhouse is like any school, it has computers, tests, and report cards. Many of my other classmates speak other languages because we circus performers are all over the world.       Then, when school is over it is time for a break. The clowns let me play with their equipment. I also play with my tiny animals; our trailer can not fit large animals.       Furthermore, it is dinnertime. We go to the pie car to eat, but we don't eat much because we are performing tonight. We do ten shows a week, so it is not all fun and games.       Finally, the show is over. I am so tired. Rohan V. #30      Room 6   Language Arts   5/21/13   Cris, the Circus Magician       Hi my name is Cris, and I work at a circus. In fact I come from   ?long line of circus performers. Since I was born here, the circus trailer is kind of my home. Also, I've been working in the circus for three years as a magician, and I'm only eight years old. My normal day is I wake up, eat at the pie cart, go to school, and practice for tonight's show. I especially like school because since we travel around the world, our geography lessons really come to life. In practice, I practice mostly basic magic tricks such as taking a coin of an empty sleeve, but I sometimes get to do advanced magic. Then after the performance I feel super tired and I sleep. Today, is a big day for me, and I don't want to blow it. This is the first day I perform an advanced trick, the vanishing act, in front of a crowd. I am nervous, but also excited. 'Now its time for Cris, the Kid Magician!' says the announcer. My hearts thumps with excitement. I enter the stage do my routine. I take out my 'magic' smoke ball and throw it to the ground. I stood middle stage to make the crowd would see me if I just went left or right making it seem more magical when I vanish in front of the crowd, making them cheer to their heart's content. I re-enter the stage and say, 'Thank you, thank you everybody!' After my big achievement I celebrate with a great meal, too excited to sleep, despite the time.

Life at the Circus           What does life at the circus feel like? What do you do in a day   of work? What is a circus? A circus is a form of entertainment with many different performers.   There are many things you could do there. You could take care   of the animals, be an acrobat, or even be a clown. Even children perform. They have school in a one-room schoolhouse.   A circus eels fun, but it could be hard because you spend a lot   of time away from home. Now think to yourself, what does life in a circus feel like?

My Life in the Circus           I learned that the circus was in town, and my family and I drove there. I had just entered the circus. It was crowded with trapeze artists, clowns, people walking on stilts, and animal trainers with elephants, lions, and other animals. I walked into the stand to wait for the show to begin. Suddenly, it began. I was suprised to see many clowns juggling, tigers jumping through rings, and men walking on ropes. After it was over, I realized that I wanted to be part of the circus.           As I grew older, I still wanted to be part of the circus. I started training, but most of all I wanted to be an animal trainer. I had always loved animals, and I wanted to train them to do tricks. I also practiced juggling in case if Ididn't get the job. I went into the circus and talked to the manager of it, and I got the job! I was so happy and started to help with the animals. My favorite was an old tiger. I fed them treats when they did tricks correctly. Soon enough, they were ready to perform after a month of hard work. One night, I performed with my animals. It was fantastic. The crowd screamed when they saw the tiger jump through several hoops. The monkeys juggled tiny balls and fruits. After the show, I was exhausted.           A few weeks later, I had always remembered that night and always trained with the animals until the next show.

The Circus   Barroom! Barroom! Baripity! Baripity! We had arrived at the circus. First, we went to the clown show. There were many many funny, hilarious looking clowns that did many funny tricks. One asked me to come down and kept pulling money out of my hair. It was very humiliating. Since then, my parents kept teasing me that I was hiding money from them in my hair and that I let that clown steal it when hey could have used that money to buy something. next we went to the stunt show. There, I saw many stunts. Some of them were the tight rope walking, jumping from a trampoline onto a horse, somersaulting from a horse, and riding on a unicycle. But, my favorite stunt was when one performer was shot from a cannon onto a whale's back and then rode the whale. In the end, we went to eat lunch. After having a spectacular lunch of cheese pizza, we decided to head back home.

The Circus                                                                T her was a girl there name was Bella Casting she came from  from   another please she travel 20,000 miles in seven months each year, visiting 150 cities. I work from sunup to sun down.                                   Here's a typical day for me 7:00 A.M I wake up, get dressed, and go to the pie car for pancakes and bacon. The crews are setting up tents, lights, and music for tonight's show. 9:00 A.M. school time. Our one-room schoolhouse travels with us. Like any school, ours has computers, tests, and report cards. Because the circus performers are from all overheat world, many of my classmates speak other languages: french, Russian, and Italian, like my family. As we travel around the country, our geography lessons come alive.                       3:00 P.M. School's over-time for a quick break. The clowns let me play with their unicycles and juggling  balls. I also play with my tiny dog, Noodle; our trail is too small for a large pet. I'd like to join a soccer team, but we're never in one place long enough.3:00  P.M. Chores and practice. I feed, water, and  groom the horses. I'm working on leaping from a trampoline onto the horse's back; it takes balance and concentration. Other kids are     practicing jugging and acrobatics. Our neighbor walks baby leopards on a leash. Trainers are working with elephants, lions, and chimpanzees.                                                                                           THE END

It's five minutes until the show starts. We are waiting patiently for the show host to come out. Some people are already eating their popcorn and snacks. Others are talking to their family and friends,and others are getting more popcorn and snacks.           The show is about to begin. The lights get dim and the stadium gets dark. Then there's a big bright light that shines on the host on stage. Everyone starts clapping welcoming him.          The host announces the clown and a funny looking clown comes out on a elephant honking a honker while doing tricks.           The clown finishes and everyone claps an throws money on stage.          The host then announces the circus acrobats when the clown leaves. The circus acrobats come out from above the tent tied onto the tight rope.          They do many types of tricks and jumps still hanging onto the rope. It seems like a pretty scary thing to do especially if your scared of heights and if the rope isn't really tight.          Everyone claps and throws some money. The host then announces the circus horses. Two horses come out and two large hoops are brought in. The host then goes up to the large hoop and sets them on fire. The horses back away then start running towards the hoops and jump.          Everyone claps and throws money and the horses leaves.  The host then announces the circus juggler. A guy in a clown outfit comes out with seven balls. As he throws them into the air, they flame up. He starts juggling the balls that are on fire and starts walking towards a small pool of water. He lets the balls fall into the water and they stop burning.          Everyone claps and throws money. The juggler laves and the host announces the circus tight rope walker. the light moves up the tent to reveal a guy on a edge getting ready to walk on the line. He walked really quick then sow then quick then slow. He made it and the crowd starts clapping and throws money.         The host then announces that it's the end of the show. Everyone who took a role in the circus act came out and bowed while the horses danced, and they gathered the money and said their good-byes.

THE CIRCUS LIFE                            2 years ago, in Mildrid, Spain, there was a young 13 year old boy by the name of Vince Epill who wanted to travel around the world. But, airfare was too expensive, going around $400 - $1,100. For a few days, he searched online and newspapers to see what jobs could let him go around the world while working too to make some more money.                       Finding The Final Job                        On the next week, Vince found an ad that needed new, experienced circus performers that get to go to more than 150 cities in less than 9 months on plane. For the whole day, all he thought about was the phrase,'More than 150 cities in less than 9 months'.He didn't care about going on plane, having to do tricks, or maybe even getting hurt so he went to the circus manager and asked if he could be part of the circus crew.  After a little interview, the manager, Taj, congrated Vince, and told him he can go see the other people and the whole circus family. On that night, Vince got ready all of his clothes, belongings, and etc. and headed to an airport and met the circus crew there.       Vince's Schedule For The Circus                         While on the airplane, Taj came to Vince and gave him the everyday schedule which looked like this:       7:30 A.M.= Wake up + eat breakfast 8:45 A.M.= Feed, water, and etc. for animals 12:00 P.M.= Practice tricks and acts 2:00 P.M.= Lunchtime 3:40 P.M.= Relax/have some sleep 5:30 P.M.= Dinnertime 10:45 P.M.= Show's over       When Vince looked at the schedule, he was surprised how long the show was, but he was satisfied with it. Now, it was the first day he is going to be in circus with a big audience. Later, instead of being scared and having stage-frieght, he was happy and confident with doing this. Vince was even happier when he remembered his dream for doing this job was to get to go around the world, but also his crew treats him nicely like family. He guessed that maybe he could do both things at once (doing circus + traveling around the world).       After 3 Years In The Circus                      Now that Vince has turned 16 years old, has gotten used to the life of a circus performer, now made contact with a big circus family of his own, and also made more than $100,000, he have had some oportunities that some famous circus managers like Tej would give him a chance to show off his tricks and acts, but he declined them all because he already has his own circus family/team and his great manager Tej. Vince and his team has been going far with the circus road and most of the world has known them for almost a century, so they are almost famous worldwide. This isn't just the end.       At The End Of The Circus Life                     Now that Vince has turned 24, he still sometimes goes back and tells these past stories to relatives and visitors, but also he sometimes goes to the circus and play a show or two to let the 21st century know what he has done in the past. His team has gone and passed to other things because of family and business problems, but Tej is still with Vince to help, but they don't really do any circus shows anymore. Now they still have a good life and all, but in their souls, they still have some drops of circus life in there, and they will treasure that great moment until they perish.

My Day at the Circus          Hi, I'm Jack Cherokee and I have a very unusual job. I work in the circus. It might sound strange and fun, but it is a very difficult job. I'm a tightrope walker and it takes skill and effort to do that. I'll tell you the life of the circus.         You see we travel in a train. First, we wake up, dress up, and we eat at the pie car. A pie car is where we eat. We also keep up with our education because we have a place where we learn like a school.After that, I practice my tight rope walking and it is very hard and I haven't mastered it,yet. Last show, I failed and fell off the tightrope. It was very devastating I got a serious injury in my leg, but now I recovered ready amaze the crowd.         My stage name is Black Jack. In four hours is the show and I am determined to master that tightrope. four hours has passed and my act is up next not even having on butterfly in my stomach. Now, everyone is watching me, sweat going down my neck. I stepped onto the tightrope and walk steadily then the crowd gased at me doing a 360 spin and land perfectly safe. Then I amaze the crowd with tricks until I'm at the end of the tight rope. My heart  was happy when I heard the round of applause. The show is over. I'm walking to bed now, feeling wiped out and I collapsed in my bed resting for the next show tomorrow.

Flipping through the air, I saw all of the crowd watching me as I was caught by my co worker, Simon. Then I flipped again and landed on the platform. When we went to bed the circus tent seemed small as they packed it away. I thought that life was tiring at the circus but I also knew it could be worse.          For the next week, practice daily and perform at night was the schedule as well as school.Make sure you finish your homework and make sure you practice your flip over and over.Everybody was always so upbeat all the time, with the exception of the poop scoopers.          Every performance same thing, the introduction, next the lions and elephants, then the trapeze act, and finally the clowns. We do the same act for a year then change it over the summer.
